Mosquitoes have two pairs of wings, but their second pair of wings are reduced to short, peg-like structures called halteres. It has a thin, long body and three pairs of extremely long legs. It has scales along the veins of their wings and long beak-like, sharp sucking mouth parts called a proboscis. It is smaller than 15 mm in length. Mosquitoes can live in almost any environment, with the exception of extreme cold weather. They favor forests, marshes, tall grasses and weeds, and ground that is wet at least part of the year.

They prefer sub-tropical climates that are relatively moist and populated with humans for nourishment. There were many mosquitos in this wooded area, but they were mostly around where bodies of water, like ponds, were around. This species is Kingdom Animalia and Class Insecta. It is a protostome.

description:
NUMBER: 20201011
SPECIES: Floating-plant Mosquito,[1] Mansonia dyari Belkin, Heinemann, and Page, 1970[2]
OTHER NAMES: There does not appear to have been a common name.[1]
SPECIMEN: 1 female, body 4.2 mm in length
DIAGNOSIS: Apex of abdomen blunt, cut-off; antennae with white scales at flagellomere joints; Wings speckled with large light and dark scales; scales broad and cut off at tip; Hind legs with narrow, pale basal bands (Genus Mansonia); Palps not more than 1/3 length of proboscis and club shaped (Cutwa and O’Meara, 2006).
LOCALITY: Master bathroom, 920 St. Andrews Blvd, Naples, Florida 34113 USA
LATITUDE, LONGITUDE: 26°6’25.7” N, 81°42’54.9” W (26.1071, -81.7152)
DATE: 11 October 2020
DISTRIBUTION: In USA most common in central and NE Florida, few in SW FL and south Georgia; common in Mexico and Central America; 1 record NW South America (Ecuador); only Caribbean records are in Jamaica, western Puerto Rico (Anonymous, 2020), and St. Croix, USVI (Seger et al., 2019).  Geographic records are obviously incomplete.  
ABUNDANCE: Lounibos and Escher (1985) found the Floating-plant Mosquito much more common than the Lake Mosquito, Mansonia titillans (Walker, 1848), in St. Lucie, Florida.
LIFE CYCLE: Dependent on permanent bodies of water with floating aquatic plants (Water Hyacinth, Eichhornia crassipes (von Martius, 1823) Solms, 1883 and/or Water Lettuce Pistia stratiotes Linnaeus, 1753.[1]  Adults can fly many kilometers from hatching sites.
DAMAGE: Has a bite that is painful to humans, very aggressive in attacking, and actively attacks at night and in daytime.  Can attack through thin layers of clothing.
DISEASE: Possibly carries Saint Louis Encephalitis and may vector other viruses.  Humans are infected with West Nile Virus in our area.
SIMILAR SPECIES: Lake Mosquito with Palps ~1/2 length of proboscis and stem-like (Cutwa and O’Meara, 2006).
IMPORTANCE: A Common Name for the Floating-plant Mosquito.
OBSERVERS: Dr. Ernest H. Williams, Jr.,[3,4,6,7] and Dr. Lucy Bunkley-Williams[3,5,6,8]
AFILIATIONS, ADDRESSES: [3]Extraordinary Professors, Potchefstroom Campus, North-West University, South Africa; Adjunct Professors, Research Field Station, Florida Gulf Coast University, 5164 Bonita Beach Road, Bonita Springs, FL 34134; [4]Dept. Marine Sciences, University of Puerto Rico (retired); [5]Dept. Biology, UPR (retired); [6]Villa Marittima, Lely Palms Community, 920 St. Andrews Blvd, Naples, FL 34113-8943; [7]e-mail ermest.williams1@upr.edu; cell 239-227-3645, ORCID 0000-0003-0913-3013; [8]Cell 787-467-2179, e-mail lucy.williams1@upr.edu, ORCID 0000-0003-1390-911x.
REFERENCES:
<>Anonymous. 2020. Mansonia Blanchard, 1901. Catalogue of Life, https://www.gbif.org/species/1649604
<>Cutwa, M. M. and G. F. O’Meara. 2006. Photographic guide to common mosquitoes of Florida. University of Florida, Florida Medical Entomology Laboratory, Jacksonville, FL 1: 1-83. http://www.gamosquito.org/resources/idatlas.pdf
<>Freeman, L. 2020. West Nile virus detected in humans in Southwest Florida; residents should take precautions. Naples Daily News, 28 September, https://www.naplesnews.com/story/news/health/2020/09/28/health-officials-warn-mosquito-borne-west-nile-virus-found-people-swfl/3561086001/

First record of Mansonia dyari from Saint Croix, United States Virgin Islands. Journal of the American Mosquito Association 35: 214-216. https://www.researchgate.net/publication/336782357_First_Record_of_Mansonia_dyari_From_Saint_Croix_United_States_Virgin_Islands
<>Williams, E. H., Jr.  and L. Bunkley-Williams. 2020. A Common Name for the Floating-plant Mosquito, Mansonia dyari Belkin et al., 1970. Research Quality Report, iNaturalist #63061212, 15 October (open access) [527][2]
ADDITIONAL FOOTNOTES:
[1]We suggest the name “Floating-plant” because these are the only plants used in their life cycles.

These 8 mosquitos (along with probably a dozen more) came swarming into my home today when I opened my door, and soon met their demise at my hands. They appear to be different species, but the identification is for the first picture.

Rockdale Pineland Preserve moth night hosted by EEL for National Moth Week. We had some rain before and during sunset but it was mostly cloudy while these sheets were up between 8:45-11:00PM. I had two sheets set up, this one with just one "DJ" blacklight powered by USB battery packs (the kind used to charge phones) and the other with two lights. To learn more about the lights used in this setup, see here: https://www.inaturalist.org/journal/damontighe/11836-diy-moth-light

description:
Wild: Protostome

The yellow fever mosquito (Aedes aegypti) is a protostome that appears to be dark-colored and are about 3-4 mm long with a striking white and black pattern on the legs and on the dorsal side. This organism is classified as a protostome since it is an arthropod with an exoskeleton, segmented bodies, and bilateral symmetry. The yellow fever mosquito is mostly found in urban areas such as South Florida, and other tropical areas. They thrive in urbanized areas, in close contact with people. This species was discovered near the Egypt Lake-Leto located in Florida in 80-degree, sunny weather; it was found traveling around until it settled in my hand. The male and female adult yellow fever mosquitoes feed on nectar of plants; whilst, females bloodied on humans to produce eggs, and are active in the daytime. Each female produces an average of 100 to 200 eggs per batch and are laid on damp surfaces such as, floods, tree holes, and man-made containers. The yellow fever mosquito transmits yellow fever, Zika fever, and the chikungunya disease.

Description: this organism s a small, dark mosquito that tends to feed on reptiles and amphibians. the body consists of the head (eyes, antennae, proboscis, and palps), thorax (legs and wings).

Habitat: I found this organism inside my house, they live inside houses. Some of them they prefer lights. They live in a sunny and hot areas.

Defining characteristics: this organism  belong to the class Insecta. The main species tend to be culex, Aedes, and anopheles.  They have small body, long legs, and small wings.

Range:  is found in North America, South America, Australia, Asia, Africa, the Middle East, and New Zealand. In the U.S., this species ranges from Virginia across the southern plains to southern California, and from as far north as southern Iowa, south to Texas and Florida.

ID Reference: https://www.cdc.gov/mosquitoes/about/life-cycles/culex.html

description:
I had been itching to go blacklighting and had vegetation monitoring work in the HID on Saturday morning so decided to nap on Friday and leave in the middle of the night to blacklight before my vegetation monitoring work. I didn't get my sheets set up till after 2AM (by then the half moon had come out). I set both sheets up along the Gate 2 Trail in Long Pine Key. I had wanted to set up a sheet in HID restoration area 2020 but it was way too windy (probably over 8 knots with stronger gusts). The mosquitoes were somewhat light but picked up quite a bit after 5AM, when the winds eased up a little. I was honestly expecting more action at the sheets but maybe didn't set them up in the best spot and I'm sure the wind and moonlight didn't help. Overall not bad but I am looking forward to trying more spots in better conditions! This observation is from the second sheet described below.

description:
I came out for some blacklighting after pre Tropical Storm Alex crossed Florida from the west, passing near Lake Okeechobee. South Florida was doused with rain, some places reported 10+ inches in Miami-Dade county. Most of the rain stopped in the early evening. There was light wind and a small shower that passed over while I was blacklighting. Moon was illuminated around 26%, temps in the mid to high 70's.

I set up three sheets in total and the one near the beginning of the Anhinga Trail was dominated by aquatic insects including toe biters and water scavenger beetles. This observation is from the third sheet described below.

description:
Set up a single sheet at a little green patch I like to visit for birding. I did the same a couple days ago but in a much more open area (and had a lot more bugs!) This time I went into a more hammock-y patch with a couple big oaks and lots of leaf litter. I used several blacklights: one bioquip powered by a battery with 12v outlet made for jumping car/inflating tires, three DJ blacklights connected to USB powerpacks. Most of the sheet visitors were small but there was a good amount of diversity. Without my macro lens it wouldn't have felt as fruitful. I was disappointed by how few visitors I had but two of the DJ lights were dead by the time I came back and the bioquip light was very weak with the big battery about to die.

I set the sheet up around 10:40PM, left and then came back to photograph everything around 2AM (I live nearby). Moon rose around  1AM and was around 57% illuminated but the area I was in was well shaded by the trees above. Wind was negligent in this area.

This adult female mosquito was found inside my apartment with many others. Mosquitoes, part of the order Diptera, are a serious public health pest, and are considered the deadliest animal on the planet because they transmit many diseases. The Mansonia genus specifically is known to be able to vector lymphatic filariasis in Africa. 

In order to prevent mosquitoes, it is crucial to remove any possible breeding areas near your property. Mosquitoes reproduce in standing pools of water, so cleaning out clogged gutters, draining tires and unused containers can help immensely to reduce mosquitoes near you. In large bodies of water like ponds, larvicides may be helpful in controlling populations.

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3419659/

I set up two sheets, each lit with two "DJ" UV blacklights in Long Pine Key. The first sheet was along one of the trails and the other was in an open prairie. This observation is from the first sheet in pine rockland habitat.

The moon was full, temps were in the low 70's and there was also some fog, so I didn't really have great conditions for attracting insects or photographing them. Not many moths and overall I didn't see an impressive number of insects although I didn't keep the lights running late into the night.

Seen while completing plant monitoring with Steve W in the Hole-in-the-Donut, Restoration Area 2019, in Everglades National Park

More info about this amazing area here: https://www.nps.gov/ever/learn/nature/hidprogram.htm

Project that includes most of the restoration areas: https://www.inaturalist.org/projects/everglades-national-park-hole-in-the-donut-restoration
At least a dozen seemingly appeared out of nowhere. They were buzzing around my legs/feet (wearing sandals) but only a couple landed while I was watching for pics
